ple, you cannot cook a catfish with Thai holly basil without the holly basil. It is truly a shame. The Pork sate has no resemblance to what the real pork sate is in all over Thailand.\nThe Isaan soup without any of the Isaan herbs can never be accepted. The Northen pork curry did not taste like anything I had in Northen Thailand. Very unfortunate. On the plus side, the service from the wine stewardess and the food servers were very efficient. We bought a good bottle of red, ordered a bottle of German white and they waived the $25 corkage fee, which is very nice. Not sure what to recommend on Thai restaurants in Vegas. Based on my personal experience, there are extremely few Real Thai restaurants in the country. Look for a place with the majority of clientele being Asians/Thai. Although, most Thais don't eat out in Thai restaurants simply because of the reason I mention mention above.\nGood eating.", "After hearing about Lotus of Siam from Anthony Bourdain and seeing the glowing reviews here on Yelp, I knew that a meal here must be a part of my visit to Las Vegas. \n\nLocated in a nondescript lot that would make one easily forget the glitz and glamor that are synonymous with Las Vegas. It was rather sketchy, not just by its looks but in actuality, if one were to go with Lotus of Siam and the Las Vegas police's notice to their patrons that asks them not to leave valuables in cars. We came twenty minutes after they opened for Saturday lunch, and there was already a fifteen-minute wait. The waiting area is rather intimate and I was truly thankful that we were able to sit in there instead of having to wait outside and experience the dry desert heat (already in the mid-80's at around 11 AM). However, we took advantage of this little wait to look up their menu and see what looks particularly appetizing.\n\nThe staff was incredibly friendly and were evidently used to handling their many visitors. We hardly had to wait for anything during our visit: the water glasses were refilled promptly, the food arrived in about ten minutes, and the check was given to us within five minutes of finishing our meal. Really, if I was a little nervous about grumpy service due to their popularity, my nervousness was misplaced.\n\nNow to the food. For our appetizer, we tried the tod mun plar, which is a popular Thai street food. It was delicious. We were able to taste the fish without getting that unpleasant fishy flavor lingering in our palate after consumption. Even the daughter, who is not a fan of fish that does not come in fish and chips form, enjoyed the tod mun plar. It was a great omen for the rest of our meal.\n\nFor entr\u00e9e, we had the northern larb, kang care, and crispy duck with panang sauce to eat with their combination fried rice. Everything was perfectly spiced and absolutely delicious. The northern larb is on the spicy side, so if you are not into spicy, maybe skip it. But if you like spicy food that offer complexity of flavors that go beyond the piquant, the northern larb will not disappoint. The kang care also delivered  and may be one of the best curries I have ever had.\n\nThe crispy duck with panang sauce from the chef's selection was undeniably the star of our meal. It was pricey, but it worked hard for every single cent of our hard-earned money. The duck was seasoned well and cooked perfectly that it did not get soggy even if it sat in the sauce it came with. But that sauce was unforgettable. It was very flavorful and just fantastic. My cousin and I had a \"friendly\" argument, which I lost, as to who can take the sauce home to eat with just plain steamed rice. Seriously, it was so delicious, I would be happy to eat that with nothing else but steamed rice for days on end and call myself a lucky girl. That good.\n\nThe fried rice was good, but I would suggest settling for steamed rice instead because it is rather heavy. I would prefer eating more of their delicious entr\u00e9e rather than fried rice. While it did not disappoint, I was rather resentful of our choice to order it because I should have known better, what with my limited stomach space and all.\n\nThe food is on the pricey side and the servings are on the small side, but if you are in Las Vegas and want to go beyond the buffets they are justifiably famous for and want to go where locals go, do go to Lotus of Siam.", "After watching the episode of Anthony Bourdain's visit to Lotus of Siam, I was completely psyched about finally experiencing the restaurant for myself first hand. We were lucky enough to walk into the restaurant at 6:00pm on a Friday night as a group of three with no reservations and get seated immediately.\n\nAfter perusing through over a 150 choices, I ultimately decided to start off with the Bangkok style tom kha kai and a Thai iced tea. I typically order this soup at every Thai restaurant that I attend, not only because it is a guilty pleasure of mine, but also because it serves as an excellent baseline comparison. With that being said, I was certainly disappointed with this dish. Obviously lime is a crucial element of tom kha kai, but this level of lime was excruciatingly overpowering, so much so that the lime was entirely the focus of the dish. The decision to use button mushrooms in the soup, instead of straw mushrooms also bothered me since button mushrooms are almost as substandard as shiitakes. \n\nAnyways, after finishing the tom kha kai I ignored the formation of any previous negative judgements, and ordered the chef's choice: the crispy duck with panang. The duck was placed atop the curry in a strategic effort to maintain the crispness of the skin, and it did just that. The duck was decadent, however, the panang was actually the highlight of the dish: spicy, creamy, well-balanced and delicious with both the rice and duck.\n\nUltimately, I highly recommend skipping the tom kha kai as I am sure that there are much better starters on the menu. As others have stated, please don't even bother to order the pad thai, there is seriously no excuse. Although I've notice some complaints from other Yelpers, the crispy duck with panang was worth the high price point. The dish fortunately provided a much needed redemption from the letdown of the tom kha kai. I'll certainly visit again to order more Northern dishes.", "Amazing amazing amazing, its the best Thai I've ever had. The crispy duck is a must have. So sad I'm leaving Vegas tmrw.\n\n\nStrongly recommend to come early (like before 6 pm)\nThe waiting time can be as long as 2 hours!", "Amazing thai food. The location is a little suspect but once inside the restaurant is nice. I recommend the prawns and crispy rice. I can't wait to go back to try more dishes.", "Amazing. You have no clue from the outside. Blacked out windows and a little \"open\" sign. You walk into a restaurant that is spacious and pumps out amazing food in copious quantities to maybe a hundred diners. Food is as good as it gets from a 12 page menu cooked by a Thai master. If you are in Vegas you have to try. Not inexpensive but worth every penny.", "An overdue review to add to the thousands of reviews.\n\nThey give you a 1-10 spice ratio. 7 is very very spicy. Get a 5 if you like spice but still want flavor.\n\nWe got the Tom Yum Soup, Glass Noodles, Khao Soi, and Red Curry. Everything was excellent except the Glass Noodles were only average. The Khao Soi is soooo good though.\n\nPortions are small, so yes we had to order 4 dishes for 2 people.", "BEST THAI FOOD IN LAS VEGAS, hands down!\n\nI first heard about this place on yelp, because I was curious on what Thai restaurant in Vegas had the highest reviews, and it was this one!\n\nLocation: hidden in an unpopular plaza, and the sign saying \"lotus of Siam\" is quite outdated. From the outside it looks very small, but don't be fool, the restaurant is way bigger than it looks!\n\nInterior: signs and many awards of the glorious food. And many celebrity photos hung around the walls. Also, they have carpet tha