 food, it definitely didn't blow me away. The curry was good, the pad kee mao (drunken noodle) was good and the chili dip was good but the prices for the chef's specials are rape! $25 bucks is not worth it. The portions are meager.\n\nIt's a great place for those who don't know what great Thai food tastes like, and for those who should know and still rave about this place, I want what you're smoking.\n\nTLDR: Overpriced dishes, small portions. \"Must try\" dishes are $25 bucks. Not worth it.", "Part of the fun of Lotus of Siam is the bizarre, strip mall, risky neighborhood location. You can't help but be surprised when you enter and are greeted by walls covered in raving reviews and crowds of people. \n\nMaybe you read about Lotus of Siam in Gourmet magazine (that's how we found it), or you saw Anthony Bourdain enjoying the Garlic Prawns on CNN, or maybe you just kept hearing how amazing it is and that you simply must dine here if you're in Vegas!\n\nNow that we've been here a few times, we have our favorites, and our favorite strategies. First, if you're going to dine in, be sure to call for reservations. We, however, love the take-out strategy and their take-out is fast! Just be sure to check your order before you leave, because they might have forgotten something, like your ... \n\nGarlic. Prawns. We almost left ours there because they didn't get included in our take-out order, and I think we would have shed tears if we had arrived back at home without them. They are crispy, flavorful, and quite unlike anything else I've tried. \n\nOur other favorites include the Kao Soi, which they make for us with just vegetables, and we enjoy most of the other items from the \"Northern\" menu, like the Tom Kha Gai. Be sure to specify how spicy you like your food -- on a scale of 1-10, a \"4\" here is pretty hot, and we like spicy. \n\nWe visit Vegas at least once a year and stop here every time. It's an adventure that's worth a little drive!", "Please don't forget to make a re