 other one is in my hometown, Fort Worth, TX. Everything seemed very authentic! The flat noodles with duck was so good! I've never had that type of dish before at a Thai resturant. The breaded fried prawns are to die for. I've haven't been to s Thai restaurant that serves prawns that way. I do not think we had a bad dish here at all.\n\nThe service here was ok. There were many times we had to wait for the waiter for quite awhile. They are possible short staff. Who knows! \n\nThe tom kha was really tasty, too and came in an authentic Thai hotpot. This is a very unique and different Thai restaurant.", "This is some of the best Thai food you'll ever find in Vegas.  A lot of nice restaurants in Vegas are overhyped and overpriced.  While the quality of food at this restaurant may not compare to the new fads of cuisine, it certainly lives up the the standards of Americans and Thais alike.  It tastes great and it's affordable.\n\nSkip the casino food and come here instead.", "This is the BEST thai restaurant in the US, in my opinion.  I cannot come to Vegas and not take a detour to eat here.\n\nFirst, MAKE a reservation and make sure you can get there slightly before your reservation as they will only hold your table for 5 minutes.  There is still always a wait.  Anticipate about a $16-$18 cab ride from the strip and about 15-20 minutes to get there depending on traffic.  Try to not go on a Friday or Saturday as it is always overly packed. \n\nSecond, its not on the strip, it's in a mini mall in the middle of nowhere.  At first, you look at the outside and it looks like a place you are not sure you want to trust eating at, but trust me...you will thank me. \n\nThey have a pretty high tech checkin system with an iPad and they actually have things organized when you get in.\n\nNow for the food, when you get the menu go straight to the chef's specialties or the Northern selection.  It's what they specialize in so take advantage. \n\nThey will ask you a scale of 1-10 for spiciness..the food is SPICY.  A 10 is only for those who have replaced their stomach with Iron.  A jalapeno is more at a level 2, a habernero is at a level 5...Scotch bonnets are level 8...I don't even know what they use.  Mind you the spice is there but so is the taste..its not like you burned your mouth and then nothing.\n\nThe wine list is also pretty impressive for a strip mall thai restaurant.  And well priced.  For $150, you can easily feed 4 people with a reasonably good bottle of wine too. \n\nFood Recommendation: Short Ribs in Penang Sauce", "This is the best Thai food in Las Vegas, and maybe the best Thai food in America. Anthony Bourdain visited here in one of his tv shows and specifically praised their Northern Thai menu selections. \n\nEverything I've ever ordered from here has been fantastic. This place is incredible, and was very reasonably priced ($10 - $15 per person, approximately)", "This place had a lot to live up to, as many reviews and articles claimed that this is the best Thai restaurant in the U.S.  I'm sure there are others that are just as good, but I have to say that this place didn't disappoint.  The garlic prawns were amazing, and the service was great!  We came just in time, 8 minutes before it opened, so we didn't have to wait long.  They came to take our order as soon as we were ready, and the food came in a flash.  Will definitely be back next time we're in Vegas!", "This place is amazing.\n\nI have been here 5 times so far and neither I nor my date have ever gotten anything we didn't like. The last time we were here I got green curry and he got panang curry (not the one with crispy duck, although we have gotten that before and it was excellent). We both liked the panang curry better but the green curry was delicious as well.\n\nUsually we also get the pork jerky or the beef jerky as an appetizer. The pork jerky is extremely juicy, the beef jerky is full of flavor, and both come with a fantastic sauce. My favorite thing on the menu is Tom Kah Kai soup, it is just the best thing on this planet. We haven't been brave enough to try the stranger things on the menu, but the menu is so extensive that it doesn't matter. If you don't know what to try, the staff are extremely helpful!\n\nWe usually order our food at a 2 or 3 which is spicy enough to make my eyes water a bit but not so spicy that I can't taste the subtler flavors. \n\nIn another review someone complained about only getting one bowl of rice. They do only give one bowl initially--that is so everyone at the table can take some and it's not just sitting there forever getting cold. If you ask for more rice they will give you as much as you want at no extra charge and it will be out about a minute after you request more (edit: apparently they charged for extra for the other reviewer--I don't know if they forget to charge me, don't charge because we are there often, or what).\n\n I have also seen a few people say that the portions are small. While I personally have always left Lotus full (and sometimes even with leftovers), it is true that the portions are smaller than at your average ten-pound-plate American restaurant. The intended way to eat (at least for the curry and saucy dishes) is that you use the rice to soak up the sauce--and since the sauce is delicious and the rice is unlimited, that is how you fill up if you are still hungry.\n\nThe pricing is extremely reasonable. Usually our bill runs about 50$ total--that is INCLUDING tax, tip, appetizer, two entrees, and drinks, and it's easy to keep it under 35$ for two people if you want. I would say this is the most underpriced restaurant in Vegas.", "This place is over rated. If you are from cities with good foods, this place will disappoint you for sure.  We tried Garlic Shrimp, Fried rice, Pad thai, and they tasted all just an average.  The price is expensive too for what you get.  The other Thai restaurant in the commercial center has cheaper and better taste foods.  TOTALLY NOT WORTH THE WAIT. THIS PLACE IS OVERRATED. DONT EXPECT TO BE AMAZED.", "This place is the Mecca for all Thai food ! I have been here twice and both times, my experience lived up to all the hype. Their Khao Soi has amazing complex flavors and is the perfect comfort food. Living in Nashville, it's impossible to find khao soi so my husband has very closely replicated this recipe but it's not the original. The staff is so helpful and friendly and their menu is expansive and full of amazing options. I can't say enough good things about Lotus of Siam. It's amazing in every way!", "This place really does have great Thai food as well as an extensive wine list. I just wish the portions were a tad larger for the price.", "This place rivals some the best joints in LA's Thai Town, but it's a bit overpriced. For the cliffs notes on what to order please see below, and I promise you'll leave  with a full belly and a smile on your face. Also it's ok if you unbutton your pants midway through your meal bro.\n\nThe Garlic Prawns \nThe Khao Soi Short Ribs \nThe Nam Kao Tod (crispy rice) \nThe Nam Prik Ong (red chili dip)\n\nAPPROVED!!!", "This restaurant is off the strip but definitely a must when you're hungry in Vegas. If you're going to eat here, skip to the back of the menu where the \"Northern Thai\" dishes and chef selections are because that's what they specialize in. Don't come here for that pad thai or pad see ew stuff. I can go on and on about the spicy garlic prawns - sooo amazing. And the crispy duck curry? Wooow. This place is obviously a local and tourist favorite because the wait time gets pretty long and while we were waiting for a table, others who were waiting with us kept saying this was the only restaurant they eat regularly at.", "Thought the food was good but just a little too pricey for my taste. Lunch ran about 12 dollars for me versus 8 at Komol right up the street. Still though, a very good meal. Service was also pleasant.", "Three of us met for dinner last night so we cou