 line of people started to form. We literally got a table when they open at 5:30pm. Service was amazingly quick and attentive. The food arrived within 5 to 10minutes. The price is on the higher end for Thai food- average about $15 to $30 for entree, but it's well worth it. The menu is very extensive and it's sorted by the region of Thailand.  \n\nThe garlic prawn comes with 8 generous pieces and flash fried with garlic seasoning. It was delicious and the shrimp was crispy. The prawn was deshelled therefore consumption is very convenient. \n\nThe crispy duck with the noodle was one of my favorite. The duck was tasty with a crispy skin. The flat rice noodle was slightly pan fried and complimented the duck really well. Pretty much, it's  similar to the Chinese chow fun (pan fried rice noodle) atop with crispy duck. \n\nThe Thum ka noon was minced pork with jackfruit. We randomly ordered this and it was interesting. It would be really good if it's eaten with rice. Overall, the food was very well seasoned and I cant stop burping after the dinner. I will definitely come back and try different entree. I'm curious how good a simple pad thai or pad see ew would taste in here?", "Hole in the wall, but SUPER WELL KNOWN! I have lived in Vegas for over a year, and a friend from home told me about it. It is off Sahara hidden in a shopping center. It looks tiny, but once you get inside - it's huge!\n\nFood - You can't go wrong with anything you order. The best things that I have tried are the Garlic Prawn, the Pad Thai, and the Short Rib Panang. The prawns are deep fried, but they are delicious! You will see the person at the table to next you have them and NEED them! I always order Pad Thai, and I found my new go-to place to get it from. The short rib Panang is sweet, and the short rib is juicy. It absorbs the flavor and melts in your mouth. \n\nAmbiance - Always busy, but definitely worth the wait. You may want to call in at least a few days in advance to make a reservation to ensure you get a table, and don't have to wait.", "Hypebeast. L.O.S. was ok, but its not head and shoulders above other Thai I've had. We had the pad thai, stuffed chicken wings, drunken noodles, and garlic prawns. The garlic prawns were good and perfectly cooked, but the flavor was a bit lacking, I thought. The stuffed chicken wings were good, and the drunken noodles were actually amazing. Everything else was not really note worthy. Not worth the hype.", "I FINALLY got to try the famous Lotus of Siam. Overall, it was pretty awesome.\n\nLocation/venue: It's located in a seriouly shady part of town in a mall I would never go to alone. The venue like...an old tired Chinese restaurant. \n\nFood: I was actually slightly disappointed that not everything was out of this world delicous...here's the breakdown\n-Crispy duck with panang curry: This was hands down the star of our meal. It's one of their signature dishes and expectations were high...and they totally delivered. Duck was perfectly crispy and juicy and the curry! OH EM GEE SOOOOOO DELICIOUS. Perfectly balanced, creamy without being heavy. Good to the very last drop. We might as well have just licked the plate.\n-Garlic prawns: Another signature dish that was very good, though not as amazing as the duck with panang curry. the shrimp meat and shell are fried separately, which surprisingly makes everything yummy crunchy and edible. The shells were possibly even better than the meat of the prawns. \n-Soft shell crab with drunken noodle: this was disapointing, especially after the first two dishes. The soft shell crab was a bit soggy and the noodles were super soggy. In fact the noodles were all stuck together in sticky soggy bricks. I feel like I must have gotten an anomaly.\n-Sai Oua (norther style sausage): don't get this. it's just...a sausage. It wasn't special. I mean, if you know what it is and you like it, sure. But otherwise, it was super disappointing and just not very good.\n-Fried banana with coconut ice cream: So crispy, so yummy, the banana and the coconut ice cream were perfect complements!\n-Mango with sticky rice: Mango was beautifully deliciously silky ripe. sticky rice was  perfectly chewy and yummy. Both of the desserts were delicious. I was way beyond capacity full by dessert and I still finished every last bite of dessert!\n\nIf you come for the duck/curry, prawns, and dessert, it's PERFECT. 5 starts. However, I am disappointed that aside from the two signature dishes the rest of the entrees were any good. Their menu is actually quite extensive...wonder if how much of the menu is actually at the level of their 2 signature dishes?", "I agree with the fact that the portions don't justify the prices, but the food is also REALLY really tasty.\n\nFOOD\n  Garlic Prawns - THE BEST!! Sooo glad we ordered this dish based on the reviews. I would've ordered another one if we weren't already so full! The prawns are huge and fried to PERFECTION. Super crispy and seasoned just right. I will definitely come back and order this every time. GO GET YOU SOME!!\n  Sea Bass w/Drunken Noodle - Lightly crispy on the outside and super flaky on the inside. Paired very well with the noodles and the flavors were well balanced. Worth trying, but definitely small for the price ($30 I think?). I'll be trying something else next time.\n  Crispy Duck w/Panang - Very yummy! You get to choose your spiciness level from 1-10 so I got 8. The spiciness wasn't spaced out very evenly, as the first couple of scoops of sauce/duck were very spicy and the last few bits weren't spicy at all. The sauce was delicious with rice, but I think I'll try the dish with mint and chili instead. I feel like the sauce made the duck less crispy. \n\nAMBIANCE\nLooks very unassuming from the outside. You would never know that such a great restaurant was located inside an old plaza like this. The restaurant itself is pretty large as they bought out the space next door and expanded. They even have a wine cabinet/wall displayed with TONS of wine to choose from. Everything from the decor to the music is pretty Asian/traditional.\n\nSERVICE\nMonday lunch service was super quick and our food came out within 5 minutes of ordering! The servers are also very knowledgeable and gave us some good recommendations.\n\nOVERALL\nDefinitely coming here again! I'm so glad we were able to stop by, especially at a good time and with no wait! Even if you've never tried or don't care for Thai food, I still recommend trying this place. The quality of food is something I've never seen at any Asian-owned restaurant.", "I almost hesitate in recommending this place because I know it just makes it harder to get a table there.  However, it is no secret.  This restaurant has won national acclaim for its authentic Thai cuisine.  What the restaurant lacks in ambience and location it more than makes up for in food quality and menu.  Extensive selection of Northern/Southern Thai dishes and an impressive wine cellar.  Garlic prawns are amazing, as are whole fish dishes of various preparations.  Spice levels go from 1 (mild) to 10 (hot) and Thai spicy (beyond hot).  Go with a large group and enjoy many different dishes to share.  Reservations are difficult.  If you can't get one, go at 5:00 and wait outside the restaurant.  Most likely you can get a table right when the restaurant opens at 5:30 for dinner.", "I came back again and got the crispy duck- OMG SO GOOD!!!!!! The duck is cooked perfectly - MUST GET THIS DISH. I think it's the best one.\n\n\nIn Summary\n- Note the store hours, they are closed in between lunch and dinner\n-Cab ride from airport is about 44 and it is also impossible to get a cab back- have to call\n-Order CRISPY DUCK, CHICKEN PAD THAI, CURRY ROAST DUCK  \nBonus: garlic prawns are pretty good too\n- Warning: You will have dreams about this place and coming back....I miss it :(", "I can't believe I have lived In vegas for over 8 years and just got around to trying this place. By far the best Thai restaurant I have ever been to. The food is so flavorful and stimulating to the palate. We ordered many different things and all were great. I'm sure there is something on the menu for everyone. Next time I will be trying the whole fried catfish with garlic and red chilies. The people next to us ordered it and it looked so yummy with a beautiful presentation. Now this place is in the ghetto ghost town part of vegas, the place looks worn down and outdated inside and out BUT who cares as long as the food is as tasty as it is. I also happened to love the owner of this restaurant. An older women who is involved in every aspect of her restaurant. I loved the way she would step out of the kitchen to check to see if everyone was enjoying the food and atmosphere. I even saw her washing drinking glasses, now that is one humble lady. I'm also assuming she has not opened another location due to the fact that she can't be at two places at the same time! Asian business lady, I salute you! You have accomplished so much to where it's said to be rated the best Thai restaurant in the USA.", "I do not know what you people are talking about when rating this restaurant higher than a two star. My wife and I had lunch several weeks ago at Lotus and wife ordered the Prawns that everyone raves about...yuc! She could not tell the prawn from the tail it was so stuck together. I ordered the duck since so many people were raving about it. Thought I was going to be sick! Worse meal we had on our three week trip. Do not go!!!", "I feel like every Thai restaurant I've been to, the food was always decent to good. I would never say \" out of this world' until I came here. It was a Friday night and we were seated right away when we got there ( no wait time, how cool is that?!) but maybe we were lucky. The ambiance isn't all that great but the delicious food makes up for the lack of decor. Anyone that thinks they've tried the best Thai food has to come here. My boyfriend and I shared the fried chicken with garlic appetizer. It came with about 7 pieces and they were all super crunchy and juicy on the inside with just the right amount of flavor from the garlic spices. For our main dish, I ordered the short rib curry noodles for my boyfriend and the pad-see-ew for myself. My favorite was the short rib curry noodles. I thought it would've tasted weird adding curry to noodles but the noodles were flat and light that it went well with the thick soupy sauce. The short rib was just so tender and it fell off my fork because the meat was so soft. I would definitely come here again the next time I come to Vegas. It's not on the strip ( probably about 3 miles off ) but so many people go there that there are taxis going back and forth from the restaurant to the strip. If you're planning on drinking, taking a taxi would be a smart idea.", "I found Lotus of Siam in Zagat's list of top rated restaurants in Las Vegas. A quick lookup on Yelp showed that it had a pretty good rating with 2000+ reviews so I decided to try it when I was in Vegas a couple of days ago. We tried calling them at around 7 pm to make a reservation but could not get through as their phone was constantly busy. We decided to take a chance and landed up at around 8:30 pm. To my surprise I found that Lotus of Siam was located next door to the now defunct Namaste Indian Cuisine a place that I had been too many times when it was open. Anyway even on a Monday evening they were completely packed and had a wait time of 45 minutes which stretched to almost an hour before we were seated. The restaurant is not very big but is a decent sized place that does not feel too cramped.\n\nAs there was only 30 minutes to closing we ordered a bunch of standard Thai dishes all at once like Crispy Fried Garlic prawns ($26.95), Pad se-ew ($9.95), Red Curry with shrimp ($13.95), Penang Curry with chicken (12.95), Combo fried rice ($11.95), Crab fried rice ($13.95) and Khoa Soi (10.95). Food was out in another 10 minutes so apart from the long wait to get a table service is pretty fast. I approached the food with a lot of skepticism as I've been burned too many times by these super hyped up places but after the first couple of bites it was clear that Lotus of Siam was legit and completely deserving of its high rating. The crispy fried garlic prawns were amazing, lightly battered, perfectly fried with a balanced taste that did not overpower the delicate crustacean. The pad se-ew was perfectly cooked noodles with just a mild sweet tang. Literally one of the best that I've had. The crab fried rice was another gem. Perfect taste without even a hint of the smell of crab. The Penang curry was also great. The noodles in the Khoa Soi were a little overcooked and hence were clumped together while the curry base was a little too watery so I thought that the dish did not come together very well. Taste-wise I thought that it had a good balance of sweet and spice, but most people in our group felt that it was too spicy for them. The red curry was not bad, just that it tasted very similar to the Penang curry. \n\nI felt that prices at Lotus of Siam were less than what you would pay at other similar Thai places but when compared with the inflated prices on the strip they seemed out-rightly cheap. Considering the overall package of service, cost and quality the only drawback that I can think about is the long wait to get a table. I'm almost tempted to deduct a star for just that, as it could seriously keep me from returning, but I'm going to overlook it and give them the rating that they deserve.", "I have been here 7 times and each time has been an amazing experience. \n\nToday however was not so great. \n\nI brought 3 co workers in for dinner after work and was so excited to have them experience the awesomeness that is Lotus of Siam. \n\nThe bar tender had me try a drink that she said was similar to sparkling blueberry sake. It wasnt. It was like lemoncello. It was good so I offered to buy my co workers each a glass of it. The bar tender told me to buy the bottle and said its a good deal. It was $70.00. She didnt even tell me ahead of time. This wasnt a huge deal because I did like the taste a lot.\n\nThen I ordered Nan Mao Tod and asked for it to not be Spivey. It came out with 4 Thai chili's in what equaled about 2 cups of rice. Crazy spicey. When I mentioned it to the waiter he didnt react at all other than to walk away.   This wasnt right as my mouth was on fire. I order this dish everytime by the way and its the main reason I come here. Couldn't even eat it.\n\nI also order the rad Nah. It was good but very few noodles and mostly gravy. \n\nThe pad see we was delicious though. Highly recommend it. \n\nOnce we finished our food. We were finishing our drinks and our waiter asked us to hurry up and leave so he could have our table. It was between 5 and 10 minutes. I dont find this to be an excessive amount of time.", "I have been there many times. Despite the long wait times, now they even automatically add 18% gratuity for part of 4... And the service is bad, rushing you to finish your food...", "I have been wanting to try this place for a long time and finally got the chance to! I'm so happy I did. All the food is super fresh and has a very rich authentic Thai taste. I've tried a lot of Thai restaurants but the taste of food here tastes a bit different, in a really delicious way! Try their Tom Kah Kai soup, it's sooooo mmmmm good!!", "I love it. The charbroiled prawns were amazing, even with mouth on fire from the chilis (we got the spicy ones). Definitely order some of the northern Thai dishes the place is known for.  The only thing we got that was just average was the Drunken Noodles - I've had better elsewhere.  But even they were devoured by the end of the meal.  I will make this a must-eat on Vegas trips!", "I love their soups and curries!", "I love this place. Delicious food and such great flavors. I went for dinner since there were some negative reviews