re that there is much that I can add.  But I do want to make one suggestion to Yelpers:  Please, please, PLEASE look at the Northern Thai section of the menu.  While the rest of the menu is very, very good (especially loved the Garlic Prawns and Sea Bass on Drunken noodles), the Northern Thai section offers dishes that you won't find at most Thai restaurants.  We had two standouts, both based on recommendations of our very attentive waiter.\n\nThe first was Kang Ka Noon, which is jackfruit in a spicy curry sauce.  An article on NPR says that these are the largest tree fruit in the world, reaching up to 100 lbs each, and high in protein, potassium, and vitamin B2 (and yes, they are quite an interesting looking fruit).  However, when it is cut up and put into a dish, the jackfruit has the consistency of an artichoke heart.  Smooth, creamy and delicious.  And the curry sauce adds the perfect spice to balance the simple sweetness of the fruit.\n\nThe second dish was Khao Soi, a curried, egg noodle dish (with Burmese flavor influences) that we had with chicken.  Much like Pho has its salad accompaniment, so does Khao Soi:  onions, mustard greens, and lime.  Oh my goodness was this dish fantastic.  It was clearly the hit of the night.\n\nSo if you are an adventurous foodie (and you likely are if you are reading reviews in Yelp), step away from the traditional and go right for the Northern part of the menu.  You will not be sorry.", "Yes, this place is in the ghetto. While on the parking lot I had a homeless man on a bicycle knock on my car window to ask me for money, but...who cares! This is simply the best food you will have. Once inside, the restaurant is nice enough, good wine selection to pair with the most delicious dishes. Every time I have been there, there's famous people eating dinner.\n\nPros: The best thai food second to none , cheap prices.\n\nCons: make a reservation in advance, hopefully days in advance because the place is small and it is always packed. You may get mugged on the parking lot, what a shame that such a spectacular place has such poor location.", "a good thai restaurant. but definitely not more than an hour wait long kind of good. plenty of empty tables but would seat us or anyone for over an hour. what is the real hype?", "been Eating here For years Very good Pizza. If Your looking for Cheap Not fresh ingredients. go to Pappa Johns or one of those places .... NYC pizza", "great food, location is not great", "this place is hit or miss.  when it hits, it's the best Thai food in the country.  when it misses, you just waited 2 hours for something you could have gotten in any town in the country.  still good, but not the transcendent Zagat darling.  i got the larb a few months ago and it was one of the best things i ever ate.  i got it again a couple months later, totally different dish and only good.  the Reislings by the glass are a perfect pairing for the spicy, sality goodness it offers.  if you've never been here, then do so, be brave MAKE A RESERVATION, but have a realistic expectation.  it might completely blow your mind, but it might also be so so.  never bad, but worth the gamble because it's reasonably priced."]
