 not outstanding. \n\nThe garlic prawns has a great texture but seemed oily and didn't have as much flavor as I would have hoped. The prawns are pulled out of the shells, but the shells are left attached at the tail, so you have the prawn and shell separately deep fried. I would never known that you are supposed to eat the shells, but, thanks to good ol' Anthony Bourdain, my husband is more up on these sorts of things than I. The texture of the breading and the shell, and the flavor and crunch of the cabbage slaw with cilantro underneath the prawns, which was coated with garlicky goodness, were the best parts of this dish. \n\nThe drunken noodles with mixed seafood weren't bad, but weren't better than any other drunken noodles I've had. \n\nThe crispy duck curry was by far my favorite dish. Red panang curry, a generous serving of duck breast with perfectly crisped skin, and some red bell pepper. Most flavorful dish on the table, with a little bit of heat. \n\nI loved the Thai lime drink--basically limeade, tart and sweet but not too sweet, with a tiny salt. \n\nThe sticky rice was meh, which was sad because sticky rice is one of my favorite things. Would've ordered it with mango, but they didn't have any, so went with coconut milk ice cream instead. \n\nMaybe we ordered the wrong things? Maybe they were having an off night? I don't know. The same meal for a more reasonable price would've gotten four stars from me, but it was way too expensive for what it was. \n\nThe service was great. Shout out to Ettel--he was absolutely amazing! He wasn't our server, but took our drink orders and cleared our table, and was SO friendly and attentive.", "I've dined at LoS at least a couple times a year and every time it's been enjoyable. It's a must-go-to every time I visit LV. Overall, the food is great and service is attentive and friendly. No wonder this place is always packed. Reservations are recommended especially if you have a larger group. \n\nThe Food:\nI can't think of an item/entr\u00e9e that I didn't like. The flavors are spot on and you can tell that they take pride in what they serve. The entr\u00e9es are family style, so everyone in our party can enjoy the tastes. \n\nHere are some of my favorites (that i remember from the top of my head)\n- Garlic Prawns\n- Pad Thai\n- Spicy Fried Rice\n- Seafood soup\n- Chicken satay (appetizer)\n- Roasted duck curry\n\nI know i've missed a few dishes but you can't really go wrong. A definite must-try if you love Thai food. Be sure to check out the seasonal items as well. \n\nOther notes:\nThe location is a bit hidden and sign (green at night) isn't flashy. You may also see a few people waiting outside. But when you walk in, you'll see that LoS proudly display articles and photos with celebs and people within the community. The restaurant is nicely lit and atmosphere can get a bit loud, but not annoying at all.", "I've wanted to try this place since I saw it on Munchies. I'm so glad I did. Though it's location is far from where I live, I feel like it's worth the drive and wait to go there. Trust me, I waited a year because i thought it would be so expensive. The prices were exceptional.\n\nWe didn't have reservations but we were quickly seated. Our server was very attentive. I never had to ask a single time for my drink to be refilled. Most restaurants have trouble with that on a busy night.\n\nOur appetizer was wonton bacon wrapped shrimp. I wanted to try it so bad that my husband and I took one each before I took a picture.\n\nWe ordered thier Tom yum catfish hotpot. We ordered it mild because I can't really take alot of spicy food. It was just the perfect amount of spicy.  \n\nWe also ordered pad Thai and penang curry duck. The serving for each dish was enough for 2 people to share. It's either that or we just really eat alot.", "If I ate at Lotus of Siam 4 times over a 4 day trip to Vegas...does that qualify me as an addict? Or just a regular on Yelp?\n\nFlying in Friday night from Newark, I search Yelp and online and find good reviews of Lotus of Siam, calling it one of the best Thai restaurants in the US. I'm a huge fan of Thai (like Somtum Der, Pam Real Thai and others in NYC) and decided to try it.\n\nThat first dinner was so good that next night, searching for healthier restaurants not far from the Strip, I decided it was easier to just go to Lotus of Siam again.\n\nOver 4 visits (3x for dinner and once for lunch), I tried:\n\nENTREES\n- Northern Larb. Think minced pork with chilis that explodes with flavor, whether you choose a spiciness level closer to 1 or 10. This was the only dish I ordered twice in my 4 visits. Be warned though, if you're not much for hot/spicy, choose a lower number.\n- Nam Prik Ong (Red chili dip). While I saw this dish mentioned in reviews, I wasn't too impressed. It's tasty, just not as much so as the Northern Larb.\n- Khao Soi. This was like a large bowl of flat egg noodles mixed with curry. Tasty but I preferred other dishes mixed with rice.\n- Kang Hung Lay (beef stew). Paired with rice, this dish was good. Fairly flavorful.\n- Isan sausages. This is Thai sausage sliced and served with a bunch of raw veggies (onions, Thai chili peppers, cabbage, etc). A good appetizer to share with friends (Though being hungry, I ordered this along with an entree for myself).\n- Pad kraprow with pork belly and minced chicken. This is usually my go-to dish at Thai restaurants (generally preferring rice to noodles) but in this case I waited a few visits to try this. If you like minced meat with basil and chilis, you'll probably like this. \n\nDRINK\n- A variety of different German Reislings. I haven't traditionally been into wine but admit I'm now sold on pairing them with Thai food.\n- Also Thai iced tea once to see what it was like. Par for the course, not mind-blowingly different.\n\nSUMMARY\nI liked this Thai restaurant so much I ate there 4 times over a 4-day visit. If you like delicious Thai food paired with wine and sake, it's hard to go wrong here.", "If I had to choose one place to eat at each time I'm in Vegas, it would have to be Lotus. Although it is off the strip, it's absolutely worth the trip. Every dish I've had here has not disappointed. I love the garlic prawns, crying tiger and chicken satay. I would suggest calling ahead to make a reservation or you'll have a long wait.", "Im in love with this Hidden Vegas GEM living here I have to say its one of the best", "In Vegas? \n\nStop gambling your life away, and Go Here NOW!\n\nI recommend the entire Northern menu.", "Incredible food, but the location is a little dicey.", "It was a good place but not as great as people made it sound.", "It's pretty expensive.  We ordered garlic prawn & whole red snapper w/ basil sauce.  The shrimp plate is looking good, but closer look half of them are skin.  The red snapper is the smallest red snapper I've seen, and I don't think it was red snapper at all; base on its texture & size, it's more like tilapia.  We're still hungry after $70 meal (for 2 dishes).  I don't think it's worth the price for the environment & taste.  I'm sorry, I don't think I've ever come back again.", "James, the technician, came in response to what we believed was a cracked shower pan in a second floor shower. Another plumber had looked at it and said he could fix the problem for \"only 800.00.\" James, after examining it, stated that it was not a crack, but a surface mark near the drain, and therefore was fine to use. After we looked closer, he was right, and we really appreciated his honesty. If we have another problem, we will have the number and name on file.", "Just above average. Certainly not worth the hype. I would maybe have given it one more star if it wasn't for the wait. I don't mind waiting for an exceptional restaurant, but slightly above average in quality and price makes it an overall loser in my book. My standards are high for Thai restaurants. Perhaps my expectations were too high but I would definitely n