.95): Pounded and shredded young jackfruit salad with ground pork, tomato, and northern Thai spices and seasoning. Another delicious Northern Thai specialty. I enjoyed the flavors of this salad more than the Nam Kao Tod and Nam Prik Ong. Goes well with rice.\n\nCrispy Duck Panang ($27.95): Crispy duck topped with Thai style red cream curry sauce with cognac. The duck is juicy and the skin is fantastically crispy. The panang is really great, too and definitely good with any choice of meat, but the crispy duck is the way to go!\n\nEverything is delicious and takes me back to my vacation in Chiang Mai. I'm definitely back for more specialties!", "This is a great restaurant. Lotus of Siam has been called the \"best Thai restaurant in North America\", and I think it's warranted.  I love the Duck Curry.  But be warned: if you say you want your food prepared \"spicy\", they make the food VERY spicy. Even if you think you can handle spicy food, you may want to order \"medium\"--which is still very hot.  The wait is usually quite long, so make a reservation if you can.", "This is a nice restaurant, hidden gem in a dated shopping plaza. Don't be deterred by the appearance of the parking lot. The food was all great, and fairly reasonably priced. Something to be noted is that spicy actually means spicy here. I usually like my food spicy, so I tend to order very spicy at other restaurants but was forewarned before coming and was glad I ordered medium spicy so that my food was still enjoyable. We had yellow curry, pad see ewe, laht nah, pork stew, beef salad and spicy mint leaf chicken. Everything was wonderful! Service was excellent. I actually thought I had left my purse there, and when I went back, they went above and beyond to be helpful, even checked surveillance cameras for me. The staff was amazing showing integrity in the way they do customer service! I will definitely be back!", "This is the best Thai restaurant I have been to. The Garlic Prawns is a must! Tried a few di