like potato chips. Love that description! The hype cannot be more real, and you likely won't be able to eat shrimp the same way again. The shrimp itself was fresh and succulent, and the highlight was the shell which was deliciously umami with a kick from the pepper and garlic. I devoured it even though I usually detest shrimp shells (hurray, finally I get my glucosamine). \n\n(+++) TOM KAH KAI (Bangkok Style; a distinctive soup of sliced chicken with coconut milk, straw mushrooms, galanga, lemon grass and a touch of lime juice) The spices and seasonings render a tantalizing complexity, bold and adventurous like an adventure to Thai street food, yet simultaneously unique and meticulous like a long-standing family recipe. I especially liked the touch of coconut milk, making it indulgent but not too creamy. Probably one of the more under-rated dishes as the garlic prawns steal the spotlight. As a bonus, this is served in a pot with an open flame, which looks exotic and neat in pictures (but the shape made it difficult to scoop the soup towards the end... when we were all craving more sopu)\n\n(++) KHAO SOI (typical Burmese influenced dish, served with egg noodles in a curry base with a touch of coconut cream, garnished with sliced red onions, lime and pickled vegetables) We decided to get the beef version since the famous duck khao soi was quite a lot pricier. Like the rest of the dishes, the flavors were untamed with rich curry paired with coconut cream, contrasted by lime and pickled vegetables. The noodles were soft and mild, quiescent in juxtaposition with the fiery broth, and the wonton crisps added a playful garnish. Beef was okay, nothing special (thankfully so since I'm running out of my repertoire of food description words)\n\n(++) PAD THAI (stir-fried thin rice noodles with eggs, green onions, bean sprouts and chopped peanuts on the side) Homey and more familiar, though still noticeably different from your typical pad Thai. Their version was not greasy and very well balanced, at the intersection of aromatic, spicy, and savory. We took the rest to-go and enjoyed heavenly leftovers two days later as our last meal in Vegas (even after our palates had been spoiled by Bacchanal).\n\nIt totaled $81 for 3 people, which is considerably more expensive than your typical Thai joint but a completely different level. The Northern Thai style is distinctive, made even more so by the chef's style. According to the website, she utilizes what has been passed down in generations. Lotus of Siam has no neon lights or Corinthian columns and is unimpressively located in a strip mall, but the food speaks for itself--flawless in technique, exotic in flavor profile, and interpretative in embedding the culinary tradition of the chef's roots.", "Saw this place from Anthony bourdain's tv\nShow. Place was packed on a Thursday afternoon. Got seated right away, avoided the buffet, went straight for garlic prawns and the back menu. Husband at a spicy curry with extra rice and I decided to go for the drunken shift shell crab. DELISH! Thai ice tea was amazing too. Now I see why this place has good reviews, authentic thai food made with amazing spices. Portions were large, and service was nothing to complain about. Just thought it was in a weird strip mall location. Def worth a shot if you're in Vegas and like thai food.", "Service is exceptional here.  Some of the best in the area.  I had the chicken shrimp salad which was a little spicy.  My daughter had Northern red curry with chicken and vegetables on a spicy level 5.  She liked it, but I had a taste and it was too spicy for me.  Looking forward to more visits at this fine establishment.", "Service was excellent.  Polite and gave good recommendations.\n\nFood listed in order of preference:\nCrispy shrimp\nSea bass\nDuck with Penang curry\nCrab fried rice\nChinese broccoli \nPad seew", "Simply awesome , great Thai food, there northern if you aren't into coconut , lots of wine to chose from , happy folks feeding the happy", "Skip the strip, get a ride to this sketchy hole in the wall. That reveals a world class thai restaurant. Definitely the best Thai outside of the Land. Try the Prawns with the flesh and the shell fried together.", "So overrated. Just because Anthony Bourdain liked this place,  doesn't mean the food is the best in the world. So expensive for thai dishes which were unremarkable and bland. The portions are small.  And the prices are big.  The only dish that was worth remembering was their popular egg noodles tossed in curry.  It was different, hence why I still remember it.  Other than that, everything else was unmemorable. I feel like this place is a tourist trap...and we definitely took the bait on this one :/", "Some of the things are really good. Curries are delicious and so are pad thai. However, I wouldn't recommend the stuffed chicken wings, too oily and the flavors are really heavy. Overall, I would recommend coming here.", "THE FOOD HERE IS DELICIOUS. You must have a reservation and do not be late because you will lose your spot.  If you do not have a reservation the line to get in is ridiculously long and you might not get a table. The staff is extremely attentive and the prices are very reasonable.", "Take away the hype and rave reviews, and you will see that Lotus of Siam delivers solid Thai food.\n\nFor years, I had heard only great things about Lotus of Siam.  I have had my fair share of Thai food so I did not understand how one place could be so highly regarded.  While I could honestly say I was not blown away by anything I tried, I did enjoy the flavors and the service leaving me with a great dining experience.  Plus, their menu is pretty extensive so if I am in Vegas again, I am ready to make another trip to try some of their other items.\n\nHere are some of the things that I tried on my first trip:\n\nNam Kao Tod: A crispy rice dish that sizzles with heat and flavor.  Each kernel of rice was almost fried to a crisp in an oil with a mixture of peppers and spices.  They provide several slices of cabbage and cucumber which help provide a nice counterbalance to the rice.  \n\nGarlic Prawns: Given the high regard for these, here I was a little underwhelmed.  When the dish arrives, you will see the piece of meat hanging from the shell, all of which had been fried to a nice crisp.  While it smells absolutely like something you would come to expect from a dish called garlic prawns, the meat itself was a little lacking in that garlic flavor.  The true flavor actually came from the shell itself which was not necessarily as enjoyable to bite into.  \n\nRoasted Duck Curry: A balance of spicy and sweet with generous pieces of duck make this a recommend.  Sure, in terms of flavor, it is what you would come to expect from your usual curries.  However, the actually chunks that were in the curry were impressive - fresh and vibrant. \n\nIn terms of service, they were really great.  The servers were very attentive to our needs and would do things to make sure everything was okay.  The parking lot is huge so no worries about that but you may have to worry about the wait.  It is usually recommended to make reservations which is possible online.  If you are unable to secure a reservation online, you can put your name on the waitlist online as well.  Make sure to arrive on time or you risk losing your spot in line!\n\nOverall, Lotus of Siam does have good Thai food that is definitely worth checking out!", "Taxi driver told us about it and it was pure bliss. Perfection. A total treat and so glad we went. We had the wings and duck curry and a few Thai iced teas. Glad I went for sure.", "The Lotus is going into my Vegas rotation from here on out. Despite visiting LV multiple times a year, I had never tried this well known Thai establishment. I was very impressed with the food and service. Based on Anthony Bourdain's recommendations on his TV show, I skipped right past the first dozen pages or so and went directly to the \"Northern Specialty\" pages. My party ordered the Khoa Soi, Red Chili Dip, and the Northern Larb. The waiter asked us how spicy we preferred on a scale of 1-10. Now I pride myself on enjoying very spicy food, but the #7 level of spicy really made me sweat. My table also ordered a sticky rice for every person at the table. DEFINITELY GET THE STICKY RICE. I wish I'd saved more room that day and ordered more at LoS, because the food was fantastic. In fact, I may need to push up my next trip to LV in order to get back to LoS ASAP!", "The best Thai resto I have ever been to. All the dishes we ordered were awesome esp the garlic prawns which are to die for. I wanna go back already! Too bad we have to drive 5hrs to get here.", "The best!!! Food is absolutely delicious!! Garlic prawns are to die for.. excellent service and definitely worth the wait. Go!!", "The crispy duck curry was amazing!!!!!! Enough said. The service was also on point, very attentive and super nice. Will be coming back whenever I go to Vegas.", "The food is very good without a doubt but very expensive when considering the portions. I did find that it had some Thai food that I've been looking for for a very long time and that no one else made so that was awesome. The garlic shrimp was great but the prices really are a bit much for what you are getting. We also ordered the crab drunken noodles and it was good but not as good as their garlic shrimp dish. This place is literally printing money.", "The food was ok. The waiters suck and food was pricey.  I politely asked for a few things (water and another side of rice) yet it did not come until the I had asked a third time. Of course when requesting my check, it did not come. I had to go to the desk.", "The food was really tasty. Try from the northern menu. Portions are medium sized. Lunch service may take a long time but it's worth it. Don't come here in a rush. Parking is very easy.", "The fried shrimp and the duck curry were both yummylicious!  I usually don't go off the strip for food in Vegas but I definitely will go back when I'm in town.\n\nI can eat a plate of fried shrimp and that duck curry all to myself (and I'm not even a duck fan).  Portions are unfortunately not that big and it is not cheap, especially for a Thai restaurant, but oh man the taste!", "The highest rated Thai restaurant on Zagat.  This restaurant lives up to that reputation.", "The portions of food are really large, curry taste very well, but the meat taste a little bit dry, and not very tasty when eat inside of meat. Pork has some fat which I don't really like, and some ducks aren't very crispy. I noticed this restaurant won the best of city in 2006,2007, but I feel not very satisfying considering the fame of this restaurant.", "The reason that I did not give them 5 stars is because I believe that Kung Fu on Valley View is a better and slightly less expensive restaurant.  But Lotus of Siam is very good.  Yelp wants the attire.  I believe that anything from full formal to basic shirt and pants would be just fine.  I would not go there in cut offs.", "There was a lot of hype created prior to coming here from my friends. Honestly, the location was a hole in the wall. From the outside, it looked pretty ghetto. However, the restaurant inside looked a lot better. There were plenty of pictures of past celebrities that has been through the restaurant.\n\nThe service was on point and attentive , nothing to complain about there.\n\nI'm not a big fan of Thai food, but this place lived quite up to the hype. We started with a squid salad and some soup that I thought were okay and a bit spicy for someone who doesn't eat spice ... Nothing special there. We ordered catfish, pad Thai, garlic prawn, and the duck dish. Out of all the dishes, the garlic prawn was my favorite and the duck would be next. \n\nOverall, if you like Thai food or want to try Thai food then I would definitely recommend this spot!", "They are best known for their garlic prawns so 